  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "So he built the house and finished it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the exterior (see on ver. 14)] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and covered",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", roofed, same word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 33:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 22:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Haggai 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". There is no reference to the lining of cedar which was applied to the interior. That is described in ver. 15] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the house with beams and boards",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Heb. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "rows, ranks.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The same word is used of soldiers ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:8, 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "of cedar.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [It has been universally held till quite lately that the roof was either vaulted (Thenius) or flat (Bahr, Keil). But Mr. Fergussen has alleged some reasons for believing that it was a span or gable roof. It is true that Oriental buildings almost invariably have externally flat(internally arched) roofs. In Palestine, because of the scarcity of timber, no other form is possible. But the temple, as we have seen, was constructed after the model of the tabernacle, and the latter, as the name almost implies, and as necessity would require, had a ridged roof (see Dict. Bib. 3 p. 1453). It does not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "necessarily",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " follow, however, as Fergusson assumes, that the temple followed the tabernacle in this respect. It is obvious that when a \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "house",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was built unto the name of the Lord,\" the form of the tent might be abandoned as inappropriate. It is true that this shape would be consecrated to them by many centuries of use, but it is also possible that in a house it would strike them as altogether ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "bizarre.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] 1 Kings 6:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the description of the exterior of the temple building is brought to a close. \"So he built the house, and finished it, and covered the house with beams and boards of cedar.\" ויּספּן is not to be understood as relating to the internal panelling of the temple-house, for this is spoken of first in the section which follows (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but to the roofing; ספן means to conceal (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 33:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and cover in all the other passages, even in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Haggai 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 22:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where ספוּן is generally, though incorrectly, translated \"panelled.\" As a verb signifying clothing, it is construed with the accusative. גּבים does not mean boards, but beams, though not \"an arched covering\" (Thenius), because beams cut in the form of an arch would have been too weak in the middle, nor yet rafters (Bttcher), because the roofs of oriental buildings are flat. בּארזים שׂדרת, \"rows, i.e., tablets (consisting) of cedars,\" i.e., cedar tablets, which were inserted in rows between the beams. This cedar-work was certainly provided with a strong covering to protect the roof and the building itself against rain; and at the sides it had no doubt a parapet, as in the case of dwelling-houses (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 22:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]